<font color="#FF0000">FEMINIST ARMCHAIR WARRIORS </font><br>
<tt>Tue Nov 18  9:33:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
UPDATE ON EXTREME MARINES<br>
   <br>
  <br>
Published in Washington, D.C- November 18, 1997 <br>
Bill Clinton's armchair warriors <br>
By Richard Grenier<br>
THE WASHINGTON TIMES<br><br>
One of the least attractive human traits is the tendency of individuals to denigrate qualities they do not themselves possess. I firmly believe this is what underlies the ongoing and perhaps incurable antipathy anti-military people feel toward our military services. Our radical feminists combine this repellent personal trait with a curious lack of logic. Why do they press so relentlessly for the advancement of women in the military services they so deeply despise? I'm talking about our departed Assistant Secretary of Defense Sara Lister, who, famously now, declared the U.S. Marine Corps &quot;extremist&quot; and &quot;dangerous.&quot; <br>
. . . . When she saw her statement in print (in The Washington Times), Mrs. Lister expressed her heartfelt regret that people were so stupid as to &quot;misinterpret&quot; her words. But she's yet to provide us with the correct interpretation, and I suspect she never will. For Mrs. Lister did not just crawl out of the woodwork. Since she first assumed office in 1994, says an Army colonel, she's had a &quot;heavy feminist agenda.&quot; <br>
. . . . One of the ways feminists have sought to rationalize their desire to hold high rank in an institution they consider contemptible has been, obviously, to make it less contemptible. When such feminists speak one has the impression that their goal is to turn the U.S. Army into a branch of the American Red Cross. Such reformed soldiers might lend a hand fighting forest fires, rescuing flood victims, and perhaps handing out cookies on the Fourth of July. <br>
. . . . But this wasn't Mrs. Lister's strategy. The year she took office, the Pentagon removed ancient taboos against women in combat and Mrs. Lister was in the thick of the fray. She strongly urged Army Secretary Togo West to authorize women in field artillery units and the combat engineers -- this from a woman who didn't seem to have the faintest idea of what combat engineers actually do. The first Americans to cross the Rhine in World War II were combat engineers, who under constant fire from the enemy built pontoon bridges for our assault troops, which followed them. It's among the most dangerous branches of the entire U.S. military. <br>
. . . . Mr. West, who often sounds like a spokesman for the National Organization for Women and who appears to know as little about combat engineers as Mrs. Lister, foolishly agreed to her idea without first consulting the Army Chief of Staff. When Gen. Sullivan heard of Mr. West's new order he instantly retracted it amid widespread embarrassment. <br>
. . . . None of this pressure for women in combat comes from the ranks, you understand, as only 11 percent of enlisted women in today's Army would ever volunteer for combat. And if war comes, 52 percent of our female soldiers would &quot;probably or definitely&quot; make every effort to get out of the Army. It must be understood that the ladies pushing most pugnaciously for women in combat are among those least likely to serve in combat themselves. They're a pure example of the fearless &quot;armchair warrior.&quot; <br>
. . . . In 1995 Mrs. Lister was enraged again. She learned that an Army research institute in Massachusetts was conducting a body building study to discover if women could ever be made as strong as men. Clearly expecting that the study would prove women permanently weaker, and that the study's results would be used to discredit the idea of women in combat, Mrs. Lister did her best to cut funding for the Massachusetts study. She also did her best to discourage all army discussion of the effects of pregnancy -- as conservatives could use this issue too to argue against women in combat. <br>
. . . . In view of her repeated pattern of suppression of evidence, Mrs. Lister's charge that the Marines are not only extremist but &quot;dangerous&quot; is curious as it's Mrs. Lister herself who's dangerous. She's studied political science, and if she weren't intoxicated by the heady vapors of radical feminism she might remember that in our century it's totalitarian societies who regularly suppress evidence against their cherished dogma. <br>
. . . . In her way Mrs. Lister is a fanatic, talking about our Marines as if they might prepare a military coup to overthrow the Republic -- as preposterous an idea as I've ever heard. And she's only one of many rabid feminists that Bill Clinton continues to elevate to positions of great influence over our military. Madeleine Morris, a former Pentagon consultant on &quot;gender integration,&quot; another intimate of Army Secretary Togo West, made her goal perfectly clear. The U.S. military must eliminate all the following &quot;masculinist&quot; attitudes: &quot;assertiveness,&quot; &quot;aggressiveness,&quot; &quot;independence,&quot; &quot;self-sufficiency,&quot; and &quot;willingness to take risks.&quot; Any sane person must realize that a unit without such characteristics wouldn't last five minutes in combat. <br>
. . . . I'd feel just a little bit better if some of these dainty armchair warriors were compelled to dive into the mud on their genteel stomachs under machine gun fire. Training isn't combat, but it might give them a clue. Another valuable clue might be gleaned if they were compelled to stand at attention while being dressed down by Gen. Krulak, Commandant of the Marine Corps -- in all our armed forces the man who has most successfully resisted feminist pressure. We live in a strange world where a military man needs less moral courage to storm an enemy machinegun nest than to stand up to our feminist armchair warriors. <br><br>
 <br><br>
